ailed investigation of the four works by R. Yissakhar Baer (ca.1580–ca.1629) of Prague sheds light on the literary strategies, pedagogic concerns, and religious motivations of secondary elites, a new cadre of authors empowered by the opportunities that printing opened up. Andrea Gondos highlights shifting intellectual and cultural boundaries in the early modern period, when the transmission of Kabbalah became a meeting point connecting various strata of Jewish society as well as Jewish and Christian intellectuals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCabalazEurope, CentralxHistoryy17th century. 0aPrintingxSocial aspectszEurope, Centraly17th century. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Mysticism. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Religious Studies. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 4aJewish Studies : Kabbalah. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Mysticism. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Kabbalah & Mysticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2020z978311149149340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438479736423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438479736/original  a978-3-11-149149-3  SUNY Press eBook Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles